Cluster upgrade with kube-ay-dee-m.

You do not upgrade kubernetes by applying a manifest. You run kube-ay-dee-m upgrade on the nodes themselves. The exam may not ask you to do a full upgrade end to end, but it will ask you to describe the order and the version skew rules, so let us get those straight.

The version skew rules are the compatibility guarantees. Kubectl can be within one minor version, either side, of the ay-pee-eye server. The ay-pee-eye server is always the highest version in the cluster. Everything else matches it or trails it. The controller manager and scheduler are the same minor as the ay-pee-eye server, or one older. The kube-let can be up to two minor versions older than the ay-pee-eye server. And kube proxy matches the kube-let on its node.

The crucial consequence is this. Upgrade the control plane first, the kube-lets after. A newer ay-pee-eye server can talk to older kube-lets, but an older ay-pee-eye server cannot talk to a newer kube-let. So the control plane always leads.

The upgrade order goes like this. On the first control plane node, upgrade the kube-ay-dee-m binary, run upgrade plan to see what is available, then run upgrade apply for the target version, which updates the control plane static pods. Then drain the node, upgrade its kube-let and kubectl, restart the kube-let, and uncordon the node. You repeat the upgrade for each additional control plane node, then move on to the workers, one at a time. Drain it, upgrade kube-ay-dee-m, run upgrade node, upgrade the kube-let, restart it, and uncordon. Draining first is what keeps the upgrade safe, moving workloads off each node before you touch it.
